There are precisely three distinct stages within the EMU framework, each designed to pull member states into an incrementally tighter embrace of economic integration. Only upon the successful navigation and participation in the third, and arguably most significant, stage is a state deemed worthy of adopting the [euro](/Euro) as its official currency. Consequently, this third stage is, for all intents and purposes, largely synonymous with the [eurozone](/Eurozone) itself.

To earn this privilege, a country must first satisfy the stringent set of prerequisites known as the [euro convergence criteria](/Euro_convergence_criteria). These aren't mere suggestions; they are the non-negotiable requirements that must be demonstrably fulfilled before a nation can be given the green light to enter the third stage. A particularly crucial component of this gauntlet involves a minimum two-year tenure within the [European Exchange Rate Mechanism](/European_Exchange_Rate_Mechanism), commonly referred to as "ERM II." During this period, candidate currencies are expected to exhibit robust economic convergence by maintaining a strictly limited deviation from their predetermined target rate against the [euro](/Euro). It’s a trial by fire, or perhaps, a trial by spreadsheet.

The overarching EMU policies cast their net wide, encompassing all [European Union](/European_Union) member states. The unspoken rule, which is nonetheless enshrined in their treaties of accession, dictates that all new EU member states must unequivocally commit to participating in the third stage. There is no real choice in the matter; they are legally bound to enter this final stage once they have, however grudgingly, complied with all the convergence criteria. Currently, twenty EU member states have successfully navigated these stages and adopted the [euro](/Euro) as their currency, with [Croatia](/Croatia) being the most recent addition to this exclusive club. A notable exception, and a testament to the tenacity of national sovereignty, is [Denmark](/Denmark). Its EU membership predates the formal introduction of the [euro](/Euro), and crucially, it possesses a legal [opt-out](/Opt-outs_in_the_European_Union) from the core [EU Treaties](/Treaties_of_the_European_Union). This rare privilege means [Denmark](/Denmark) is not, mercifully, compelled to embark on the third stage of this economic odyssey.

